Definition 2.2. Two local conformal nets on the line (in their vacuum sector) $\{\mathcal{A}\}$ and $\{\mathcal{B}\}$, or better $(\{\mathcal{A}\},U_{\mathcal{A}},\Omega_{\mathcal{A}},\mathcal{H}_{\mathcal{A}})$ and $(\{\mathcal{B}\},U_{\mathcal{B}},\Omega_{\mathcal{B}},\mathcal{H}_{\mathcal{B}})$, are isomorphic, or unitarily equivalent, if there exists a unitary operator $W:\mathcal{H}_{\mathcal{A}}\rightarrow\mathcal{H}_{\mathcal{B}}$ which intertwines the two quadruples, i.e., $W\mathcal{A}(I)W^{*}=\mathcal{B}(I)$ for all $I\in\mathcal{I}$, $WU_{\mathcal{A}}(g)W^{*}=U_{\mathcal{B}}(g)$ for all $g\in\mathsf{M\ddot{o}b}$ and $W\Omega_{\mathcal{A}}=\Omega_{\mathcal{B}}$. We write $\{\mathcal{A}\}\cong\{\mathcal{B}\}$ for isomorphic nets.
Definition 4.2. Given a unital tensor full subcategory $\mathcal{C}\subset\operatorname{DHR}\{\mathcal{A}\}$ we define its dual as $\mathcal{C}^{\perp}:=\big{\{}a\in\mathcal{A}:\sigma(a)=a,\,\sigma\in\mathcal{C% }\big{\}}.$
Definition 8.2. A UMTC $\mathcal{C}$ is called a prime UMTC if $\mathcal{C}\not\simeq\operatorname{Vec}$ and every full unitary fusion subcategory $\mathcal{D}\subset\mathcal{C}$ which is again a UMTC is either $\mathcal{D}\simeq\mathcal{C}$ or $\mathcal{D}\simeq\operatorname{Vec}$ as UBTCs.
Definition 2.4. We say that a category $\mathcal{K}$ has enough $\lambda$-pure quotients if for each object $K$ there is, up to isomorphism, only a set of morphisms $f:L\to K$ such that $f=h\cdot g$, $g$ $\lambda$-pure epimorphism implies that $g$ is an isomorphism.
