Definition 5.1. Let $\mathcal{P}=((\mathcal{S},\mathcal{T}),(\mathcal{U},\mathcal{V}))$ be a concentric TCP. Define the set of mutable cotorsion pairs on $\mathcal{C}$ with respect to $\mathcal{P}$ to be $\mathfrak{M}_{\mathcal{P}}=\Set{(\mathcal{A},\mathcal{B})\in\mathfrak{CP}(% \mathcal{C})}{\begin{array}[]{c}\mathcal{S}\subseteq\mathcal{A}\subseteq% \mathcal{U}\\ \mathcal{V}\subseteq\mathcal{B}\subseteq\mathcal{T}\end{array},\mathrm{Ext}^{1% }_{\mathcal{Z}/\mathcal{I}}(\sigma(\mathcal{A}/\mathcal{I}),\omega(\mathcal{B}% /\mathcal{I}))=0}.$ Remark that $\mathcal{S}\subseteq\mathcal{A}$ implies $\mathcal{B}\subseteq\mathcal{T}$, and $\mathcal{V}\subseteq\mathcal{B}$ implies $\mathcal{A}\subseteq\mathcal{U}$. For another description of $\mathfrak{M}_{\mathcal{P}}$ under the assumption of the following (I)+(II), see Corollary 5.18.
Definition 1.1. Let $\mathcal{U},\mathcal{V}\subseteq\mathcal{C}$ be full additive subcategories closed under isomorphisms and direct summands. The pair $(\mathcal{U},\mathcal{V})$ is called a cotorsion pair on $\mathcal{C}$ if it satisfies the following. (i) $\mathcal{C}=\mathcal{U}\ast\mathcal{V}[1]$. (ii) $\mathrm{Ext}^{1}(\mathcal{U},\mathcal{V})=0$, where $\mathrm{Ext}^{1}(X,Y)=\mathcal{C}(X,Y[1])$ for any $X,Y\in\mathcal{C}$. Denote the set of cotorsion pairs on $\mathcal{C}$ by $\mathfrak{CP}(\mathcal{C})$. In a cotorsion pair $(\mathcal{U},\mathcal{V})$, subcategories $\mathcal{U}$ and $\mathcal{V}$ determine each other, as right and left orthogonal categories. Indeed, we have $\mathcal{V}=\mathcal{U}[-1]^{\perp}$ and $\mathcal{U}={}^{\perp}\mathcal{V}[1]$. Here, $\mathcal{U}[-1]^{\perp}$ denotes the full subcategory of $\mathcal{C}$ consisting of objects $C\in\mathcal{C}$ satisfying $\mathcal{C}(\mathcal{U}[-1],C)=0$. Similarly for ${}^{\perp}\mathcal{V}[1]$. In particular, $\mathcal{U}$ and $\mathcal{V}$ are closed under extensions. A pair $(\mathcal{U},\mathcal{V})$ is cotorsion pair if and only if $(\mathcal{U}[-1],\mathcal{V})$ is torsion pair.
Definition 5.19. Let $\mathcal{P}$ be a concentric TCP satisfying (I)+(II). Define the mutation on $\mathfrak{M}_{\mathcal{P}}$ to be a $\mathbb{Z}$-action, obtained by pulling back the shift $\mathbb{Z}$-action on $\mathfrak{CP}(\mathcal{Z}/\mathcal{I})$. Namely, for any $n\in\mathbb{Z}$, we define as $\mu_{n}=\mathbb{I}\circ[n]\circ\mathbb{R}$. This gives a $\mathbb{Z}$-action $\mathbb{Z}\times\mathfrak{M}_{\mathcal{P}}\to\mathfrak{M}_{\mathcal{P}}$.
Definition 4.1. The functor $\langle 1\rangle\colon\mathcal{Z}/\mathcal{I}\to\mathcal{U}/\mathcal{I}$ is defined in the following way, similarly as in [Ha, section 2] and [IY, Proposition 2.6, Definition 4.1]. (i) For any $Z\in\mathcal{Z}$, there is a distinguished triangle $U[-1]\to Z\to I\to U\quad(U\in\mathcal{U},I\in\mathcal{I}).$ (ii) For any (other) $Z^{\prime}\in\mathcal{Z}$ and any distinguished triangle $U^{\prime}[-1]\to Z^{\prime}\to I^{\prime}\to U^{\prime}\quad(U^{\prime}\in% \mathcal{U},I^{\prime}\in\mathcal{I}),$ we have a bijection $(\mathcal{Z}/\mathcal{I})(Z,Z^{\prime})\overset{\cong}{\longrightarrow}(% \mathcal{U}/\mathcal{I})(U,U^{\prime})\ ;\ \underline{z}\mapsto\underline{u},$ where $z$ and $u$ fit into a morphism of triangles $(z,i,u)$ from $(\ref{Triaposhi1})$ to $(\ref{Triaposhi2})$. Using these (i),(ii), we define as follows. (1) For each object $Z\in\mathrm{Ob}(\mathcal{Z}/\mathcal{I})$, choose $Z\langle 1\rangle=U$ as in (i). (2) For any morphism $\underline{z}$ in $\mathcal{Z}/\mathcal{I}$, define the morphism $\underline{z}\langle 1\rangle$ by $\underline{z}\langle 1\rangle=\underline{u}$ as in (ii). Then we obtain a fully faithful functor $\langle 1\rangle\colon\mathcal{Z}/\mathcal{I}\to\mathcal{U}/\mathcal{I}$, determined uniquely up to natural isomorphism. The functor $\langle-1\rangle\colon\mathcal{Z}/\mathcal{I}\to\mathcal{T}/\mathcal{I}$ is defined dually. Moreover, the same argument as in (ii) shows the existence of a natural bijection $(\mathcal{U}/\mathcal{I})(Z\langle 1\rangle,Z^{\prime})\cong(\mathcal{T}/% \mathcal{I})(Z,Z^{\prime}\langle-1\rangle)$ for any $Z,Z^{\prime}\in\mathcal{Z}$.
Definition 1.5. $($[N2, Definition 2.7]$)$ Let $(\mathcal{S},\mathcal{T}),(\mathcal{U},\mathcal{V})$ be two cotorsion pairs on $\mathcal{C}$. The pair $\mathcal{P}=((\mathcal{S},\mathcal{T}),(\mathcal{U},\mathcal{V}))$ is called a twin cotorsion pair $($TCP for short$)$ on $\mathcal{C}$ if it satisfies $\mathrm{Ext}^{1}(\mathcal{S},\mathcal{V})=0$. Note that this condition is equivalent to $\mathcal{S}\subseteq\mathcal{U}$, and also to $\mathcal{V}\subseteq\mathcal{T}$. Remark that any cotorsion pair $(\mathcal{U},\mathcal{V})$ on $\mathcal{C}$ can be regarded as a twin cotorsion pair $((\mathcal{U},\mathcal{V}),(\mathcal{U},\mathcal{V}))$. A twin cotorsion pair $\mathcal{P}=((\mathcal{S},\mathcal{T}),(\mathcal{U},\mathcal{V}))$ is said to be degenerated to a single cotorsion pair if it satisfies $\mathcal{S}=\mathcal{U}$ (equivalently, $\mathcal{T}=\mathcal{V}$).
