Definition 2.1. We define ${\rm Ver}_{p}^{+}$ to be the abelian subcategory of ${\rm Ver}_{p}$ generated by $L_{i}$ for $i$ odd, and define ${\rm Ver}_{p}^{-}$ to be the abelian subcategory of ${\rm Ver}_{p}$ generated by $L_{i}$ for $i$ even.
Definition 4.1. Let $d_{+}(X):=\mathop{\mathrm{FPdim}}\nolimits(F(X)^{+}),\;\;d_{-}(X):=\mathop{% \mathrm{FPdim}}\nolimits(F(X)^{-}),$ Define the super Frobenius-Perron dimension of $X$ as ${\rm SFPdim}(X):=d_{+}(X)-d_{-}(X).$
Definition 2.9. ([EHO]) We say that the symmetric $p$-adic dimension ${\rm Dim}_{+}(X)$ of $X$ is $d$ if $\sum_{j}\dim(S^{j}X)z^{j}=(1-z)^{-d},$ and say that the exterior $p$-adic dimension ${\rm Dim}_{-}(X)$ of $X$ is $d$ if $\sum_{j}\dim(\wedge^{j}X)z^{j}=(1+z)^{d}.$
Definition 1.11 (Action of a groupoid on a manifold). Let ${{\mathcal{G}}}$ be a Lie groupoid $G_{1}\rightrightarrows G_{0}$ and $P$ a manifold in ${\mathfrak{S}}$. An action of ${\mathcal{G}}$ on $P$ is given by (i) an anchor map $a:P\to G_{0}$ (ii) an action map $\mu:G_{1}\times_{s,a}P\to P$ such that $t(k)=a(k\cdot p)$ for all $(k,p)\in G_{1}\times P$ with $s(k)=a(p)$, satisfying the standard action properties: $e(a(p))\cdot p=p$ and $(k\cdot p)\cdot h=(gh)\cdot p$ whenever the operations are defined.
Definition 2.3. For an invariant open set $U\subset G_{0}$, we will say that the restricted groupoid ${\mathcal{U}}$ is ${\mathcal{G}}$-categorical if the inclusion map $i_{{\mathcal{U}}}\colon{\mathcal{U}}\to{\mathcal{G}}$ is groupoid homotopic to a generalized constant map $(\epsilon,c)$.
Definition 1.5. A category fibred in groupoids $\mathfrak{X}$ over $\mathfrak{S}$ is a stack over $\mathfrak{S}$ if the following gluing axioms hold: (i) For any smooth manifold $X$ in $\mathfrak{S}$, any two objects $x,y$ in ${\mathfrak{X}}$ lying over $X$ and any two isomorphisms $\phi,\psi:x\rightarrow y$ over $X$, such that $\phi|U_{i}=\psi|U_{i}$ for all $U_{i}$ in a covering $\{U_{i}\rightarrow X\}$ it follows that $\phi=\psi$. (ii) For any smooth manifold $X$ in $\mathfrak{S}$, any two objects $x,y\in{\mathfrak{X}}$ lying over $X$, any covering $\{U_{i}\rightarrow X\}$ and, for every $i$, an isomorphism $\phi_{i}:x|U_{i}\rightarrow y|U_{i}$, such that $\phi|U_{ij}=\phi_{j}|U_{ij}$ for all $i,j$, there exists an isomorphism $\phi:x\rightarrow y$ with $\phi|U_{i}=\phi$ for all $i$. (iii) For any smooth manifold $X$ in $\mathfrak{S}$, any covering $\{U_{i}\rightarrow X\}$, any family $\{x_{i}\}$ of objects $x_{i}$ in the fibre ${\mathfrak{X}}_{U_{i}}$ and any family of morphisms $\{\phi_{ij}\}$, where $\phi_{ij}:x_{i}|U_{ij}\rightarrow x_{j}|U_{ij}$ satisfying the cocycle condition $\phi_{jk}\circ\phi_{ij}=\phi_{ik}$ in ${\mathfrak{X}}(U_{ijk})$ there exist an object $x$ lying over $X$ with isomorphisms $\phi_{i}:x|U_{i}\rightarrow x_{i}$ such that $\phi_{ij}\circ\phi_{i}=\phi_{j}$ in ${\mathfrak{X}}(U_{ij})$.
Definition 1.19 (Restricted substack). Let $\pi:{\mathfrak{X}}\to{\mathfrak{S}}$ be a differentiable stack with atlas $x:X\to{\mathfrak{X}}$ and $U\subset X$ be an open set. Consider the full subcategory ${\mathfrak{U}}$ on $U_{0}$ and let $\pi^{\prime}:=\pi\circ i$, where $i:{\mathfrak{U}}\to{\mathfrak{X}}$ is the inclusion. We say that ${\mathfrak{U}}$ with the projection $\pi^{\prime}:{\mathfrak{U}}\to{\mathfrak{S}}$ is the restricted substack of ${\mathfrak{X}}$ to ${\mathfrak{U}}$.
Definition 1.10. A Lie groupoid $\mathcal{G}$ is a groupoid in the category $\mathfrak{S}$ of smooth manifolds, i. e. ${G_{1}\rightrightarrows G_{0}}$ such that the space of arrows $G_{1}$ and the space of objects $G_{0}$ are smooth manifolds and all structure morphisms $m:G_{1}\times_{G_{0}}G_{1}\rightarrow G_{1},\,s,t:G_{1}\rightarrow G_{0},\,i:G% _{1}\rightarrow G_{0},\,e:G_{0}\rightarrow G_{1}$ are smooth maps and additionally the source map $s$ and the target map $t$ are submersions.
Definition 2.1. Let $G_{1}\rightrightarrows G_{0}$ be a Lie groupoid. An open set $U\subset G_{0}$ is invariant if $t(s^{-1}(U))\subset U$. The restricted groupoid ${\mathcal{U}}$ to an invariant set $U\subset G_{0}$ is the full groupoid over $U$. In other words, $U_{0}=U$ and $U_{1}=\{g\in G_{1}:s(g),t(g)\in U\}$. We write ${\mathcal{U}}={\mathcal{G}}|_{U}\subset{\mathcal{G}}$.
Definition 1.15. Let ${\mathcal{G}}={G_{1}\rightrightarrows G_{0}}$ and ${\mathcal{H}}=H_{1}\rightrightarrows H_{0}$ be Lie groupoids. A morphism of Lie groupoids is a smooth functor $\phi:{\mathcal{G}}\rightarrow{\mathcal{H}}$ given by two smooth maps $\phi=(\phi_{1},\phi_{0})$ with $\phi_{0}:G_{0}\rightarrow H_{0},\,\phi_{1}:G_{1}\rightarrow H_{1}$ which commute with all structure morphisms of the groupoids. A morphism $\phi:{\mathcal{G}}\rightarrow{\mathcal{H}}$ of Lie groupoids is a Morita morphism or essential equivalence if (i) $\phi_{0}:G_{0}\rightarrow H_{0}$ is a surjective submersion, (ii) the diagram $\xy\xymatrix{G_{1}\ar[r]^{(s,t)}\ar[d]_{\phi_{1}}&G_{0}\times G_{0}\ar[d]^{% \phi_{0}\times\phi_{0}}\\ H_{1}\ar[r]^{(s,t)}&H_{0}\times H_{0}}\endxy$ is cartesian, i. e. $G_{1}\cong H_{1}\times_{H_{0}\times H_{0}}G_{0}\times G_{0}$. Two Lie groupoids $\mathcal{G}$ and $\mathcal{H}$ are Morita equivalent, if there exists a third Lie groupoid $\mathcal{K}$ and Morita morphisms ${\mathcal{G}}\stackrel{{\scriptstyle\phi}}{{\leftarrow}}{\mathcal{K}}\stackrel% {{\scriptstyle\psi}}{{\rightarrow}}{\mathcal{H}}$
Definition 3.1. Let $\pi:{\mathfrak{X}}\to{\mathfrak{S}}$ be a differentiable stack with atlas $x:X\to{\mathfrak{X}}$ and $U\subset X$ be an open set. We will say that the restricted substack ${\mathfrak{U}}$ is ${\mathfrak{X}}$-categorical if the inclusion map $i_{{\mathfrak{U}}}\colon{\mathfrak{U}}\to{\mathfrak{X}}$ is homotopic to a constant morphism $c:{\mathfrak{U}}\to{\mathfrak{X}}$ between differentiable stacks.
Definition 1.1. A category fibred in groupoids over $\mathfrak{S}$ is a category $\mathfrak{X}$, together with a functor $\pi_{\mathfrak{X}}:\mathfrak{X}\rightarrow\mathfrak{S}$ such that the following axioms hold: (i) For every morphism $V\rightarrow U$ in $\mathfrak{S}$, and every object $x$ of $\mathfrak{X}$ lying over $U$, there exists an arrow $y\rightarrow x$ in $\mathfrak{X}$ lying over $V\rightarrow U$, (ii) For every commutative triangle $W\rightarrow V\rightarrow U$ in $\mathfrak{S}$ and morphisms $z\rightarrow x$ lying over $W\rightarrow U$ and $y\rightarrow x$ lying over $V\rightarrow U$, there exists a unique arrow $z\rightarrow y$ lying over $W\rightarrow V$ such that the composition $z\rightarrow y\rightarrow x$ is the morphism $z\rightarrow x$.
Definition 1.20 (Constant morphism). Let $c:{\mathfrak{X}}\to{\mathfrak{Y}}$ be a smooth morphism between differentiable stacks. We say that $c$ is a constant morphism if there are presentations $X\to{\mathfrak{X}}$ and $Y\to{\mathfrak{Y}}$ such that the induced morphism from the fibered product $X\times_{{\mathfrak{Y}}}Y\to Y$ is a constant map.
Definition 2.4. Let ${\mathcal{G}}=G_{1}\rightrightarrows G_{0}$ be a Lie groupoid. The groupoid LS-category, $\mbox{\rm cat}({\mathcal{G}})$, is the least number of invariant open sets $U$ needed to cover $G_{0}$ such that the restricted groupoid ${\mathcal{U}}$ is ${\mathcal{G}}$-categorical. If $G_{0}$ cannot be covered by a finite number of such open sets, we will say that $\mbox{\rm cat}({\mathcal{G}})=\infty$.
Definition 1.12 (Groupoid torsor). Let ${{\mathcal{G}}}$ be a Lie groupoid $G_{1}\rightrightarrows G_{0}$ and $S$ a manifold in ${\mathfrak{S}}$. A ${\mathcal{G}}$-torsor over $S$ is given by (i) a manifold $P$ together with (ii) a surjective submersion $\pi:P\rightarrow S$ and (iii) an action of ${\mathcal{G}}$ on $P$ such that for all $p,p^{\prime}\in P$ with $\pi(p)=\pi(p^{\prime})$ there exists a unique $k\in G_{1}$ such that $k\cdot p=p^{\prime}$
Definition 1.6. A stack $\mathfrak{X}$ over $\mathfrak{S}$ is a differentiable or smooth stack if there exists a smooth manifold $X$ and a surjective representable submersion $x:X\rightarrow{\mathfrak{X}}$, i. e. there exists a smooth manifold $X$ together with a morphism of stacks $x:X\rightarrow{\mathfrak{X}}$ such that for every smooth manifold $U$ and every morphism of stacks $U\rightarrow{\mathfrak{X}}$ the fibre product $X\times_{\mathfrak{X}}U$ is representable and the induced morphism of smooth manifolds $X\times_{\mathfrak{X}}U$ is a surjective submersion.
Definition 3.2. Let $\pi:{\mathfrak{X}}\to{\mathfrak{S}}$ be a differentiable stack with atlas $x:X\to{\mathfrak{X}}$. The stack LS-category, $\mbox{\rm cat}({\mathfrak{X}})$, is the least number of open sets $U$ needed to cover $X$ such that the restricted substack ${\mathcal{U}}$ is ${\mathfrak{X}}$-categorical. If $X$ cannot be covered by a finite number of such open sets, we will say that $\mbox{\rm cat}({\mathfrak{X}})=\infty$.
Definition 1.18 (Smooth morphism). An arbitrary morphism ${\mathfrak{X}}\to{\mathfrak{Y}}$ of differentiable stacks is smooth, if there are atlases $X\to{\mathfrak{X}}$ and $Y\to{\mathfrak{Y}}$ such that the induced morphism from the fibered product $X\times_{{\mathfrak{Y}}}Y\to Y$ in the diagram below is a smooth map between manifolds. $\xy\xymatrix{X\times_{{\mathfrak{Y}}}Y\ar[r]\ar[dd]&X\ar[d]\\ &{\mathfrak{X}}\ar[d]\\ Y\ar[r]&{\mathfrak{Y}}}\endxy$
Definition 2.2. We say that the map $(\epsilon,c):{\mathcal{K}}\overset{\epsilon}{\leftarrow}{\mathcal{K}}^{\prime}% \overset{c}{\to}{\mathcal{G}}$ is a generalized constant map if for all $x\in K^{\prime}_{0}$ there exists $g\in G_{1}$ with $s(g)=x_{0}$ such that $c(x)=t(g)$ for a fixed $x_{0}\in G_{0}$.
Definition 20. For any operad $O$, we define an $O$-$n$-tree to be a $U(O)$-$n$-tree, where $U(O)$ is the underlying collection of $O$. We define an $O$-tree to be a $U(O)$-tree.
Definition 30. For any operad $O$ and any set $M$ we define an $(O,M)$-$n$-tree to be a $(U(O),M)$-$n$-tree. An $(O,M)$-tree is a $(U(O),M)$-tree.
Definition 10. We define a $C$-$n$-tree to be an isomorphism class of $C$-labelled planar $n$-trees. We define a $C$-tree to be a $C$-$n$-tree for any $n=0,1,2,\dots$. We denote the set of $C$-$n$-trees by $C\mathrm{Tree}_{n}$.
Definition 25. An $n$-tree together with a map $\ell\colon E\to[0,\infty)$ is called an $n$-tree with lengths. For any $e\in E$ we call $\ell(e)$ the length of $e$.
Definition 40. A morphism of topological operads $f\colon O\to O^{\prime}$ is a weak equivalence if for every $n$ the map $f_{n}$ is a weak homotopy equivalence. We say that $f$ is a homotopy equivalence if there exists $g\colon O^{\prime}\to O$ such that $g_{n}$ is a homotopy inverse to $f_{n}$ for every $n$.
Definition 16. Given an $n$-tree $T=(V,E,s,t)$, we call an edge $e\in E$ internal if its source and target both lie in $V$. We call the edges that are not internal external.
Definition 9. Given two $C$-labelled planar $n$-trees, we say they are isomorphic if there is an isomorphism of their underlying planar $n$-trees such that the labelling of each vertex in the first equals the labelling of the corresponding vertex in the second.
Definition 3. We call an $n$-tree with just one vertex a corolla.
Definition 28. Let $C$ be a collection and $M$ a set. A $(C,M)$-labelled planar $n$-tree is a $C$-$n$-tree together with a map $\ell\colon E\to M$ assigning a label in $M$ to each edge. An isomorphism of $(C,M)$-labelled planar $n$-trees is an isomorphism of the underlying $C$-$n$-trees that preserves the labelling of edges.
